passages.text: EUROPE | Paper & Packaging
Read Across to European Box Makers - Privately-Owned Program 2Q25

Program #5 EU cobard and #3- 4 corrugated sheet producer (after SW/ IP). Scale, low- cost cobard (mills) or integration into corrugated/boxes is needed, with high- cost players' loss making. Call aligned with listed peers noting stabilisation in vols, and cobard bottoming in Sep (JEFE stable MoM vs bears at small declines). Overall, read across from price/vol comments to IP/SW/MNDI small negative. Positive surprises would be industry closures or 4Q hike.

2Q25 Results & Commentary: Program saw modest increase in demand in 1Q25 with \(+0\%\) YoY corrugated vols (vs EU box mkt \(+2\%\) ), but this was offset in the 2Q with \(- 5.5\%\) YoY impacted by weaker UK & Germany markets. Poland was regionally stronger. This compares to EU box market volumes in 2Q25 of \(- 1\%\) and peers (SW: \(0\%\) ; IP: LSD- ; MNDI: LSD+). Corrugated sheets which is used to make boxes, saw prices rise approx \(+5\%\) QoQ (+8% YoY in 2Q25), following the recycled containerboard (paper for boxes) hikes in Feb- 25 with 1- 2month lag.

3Q25 Outlook & Commentary: Program expects slightly higher 3Q vols YoY (JEFE industry vols to stabilise at \(+0 - 1\%\) in 3Q after \(- 1\%\) in 2Q). Waste paper (OCC) costs seen as lower is known (every 1mT cobard needs 1.1mT OCC), with OCC prices €60/t off 2Q highs towards €120/t, and JEF estimates that OCC stabilises around the current levels (cost tailwind to EBITDA QoQ into 3Q for cobard mills). Lower recycled cobard prices also known given €30/ t July and €40/t Aug declines in Germany prices (here). Price declines in recycled cobard in July/Aug of €70/t are more than €60/t waste paper relief implying pressure to higher cost mills.

Discussions for recycled cobard prices in Sep- 25 are still ongoing (bears arguing further pressure in Germany price data on 11 Sep- 25 vs JEFE stable prices unless OCC declines further), however, interestingly Program call noted some discussion for Oct- 25 price increases into seasonally stronger holiday period. Our very limited other industry channel checks had also mentioned we could see a cost push price increase if we see up- tick in box demand or closures (Note: we have not seen any publicly announced price hikes, or hikes reported by trade press). Program similar to 2Qr view, also expects to see some cobard capacity closures in EU, but they did not quantify the amount/timing. We want to see the EU follow the US example and close capacity, and believe IP will focus on its EU old DS Smith footprint next (here).

Corrugated board prices seen following recycled cobard lower with a time lag. Program thus guiding for slight QoQ decline for 3Q25 and some further declines in 4Q25. If recycled cobard prices move in Oct this would feed through to higher corrugated prices with a lag supporting 4Q and 1H26 corrugated & box makers.

Program Background (#5 EU cobard producer): Program is a leading family- owned producer of recycled containerboard (paper used for boxes) and corrugated board (cardboard sheets used to make boxes). They approx \(85\%\) integrated containerboard & corrugated sheet/board producer, but do not produce boxes. Program is the European #5 in recycled containerboard with \(6\%\) capacity share (1.85mT across three mills) and the #3- 4 corrugated sheet producer after SmurfitWestRock International Paper (DS Smith) and SAICA, with 16 production sites across Germany, Poland, Czech Republic, France, Italy & the UK (approx 2mT corrugated capacity, which includes its new 200kT Italy PW16 corrugated project for €126m).

Program's sales in LTM were €1.4bn sales and EBITDA €161m. With 1H25 EBITDA of 11.3% margin and in 2Q25 was at \(10.9\%\) (2014- 1H25 avg: \(19\%\) ). Leverage at 5.3x net debt to EBITDA in 3Q25, on cyclically low earnings.
Exhibit 1 - European Containerboard & Corrugated EBITDA margins Europe is a two- tiered market - JEFE that approx \(15\%\) of higher cost cobard & corrugated producers are making EBITDA/cash losses.
Source: Jefferies estimates, Company data (note: We do not adjust histories for US GAAP and IP uses DS Smith data for 30 April prior to acquisition)
We see larger or low- cost producers as relative winners in challenging EU market vs smaller higher cost producers.
Exhibit 2 - European Containerboard - Assessing Average Industry EBITDA Margins
Source: Jefferies estimates, RISI Mill Intelligence (Note: We take industry prices less average industry cash costs for an estimated EBITDA margin)
Exhibit 3 - European OCC (Old Corrugated Container) in EUR/t Waste paper raw material (1.1mT OCC for every 1mT of recycled cobard)
Source: RISI (FOEX), Jefferies
Exhibit 4 - Germany Containerboard Index Prices
Source: RISI (FOEX), Jefferies
Exhibit 5 - Corrugated Board Price Development (+8% YoY and +5% QoQ) Corrugated Board is 50-70% cost of a box
Our 2026E Price Target of \(61 is based on our\) 4,549 mil EBITDA estimate and an EV/EBITDA multiple of 9.0x.

Risks include containerboard and box volumes / prices decrease on weaker macro. Management is unable to generate the targeted EBITDA improvements from its commercial initiatives and cost reduction programs, or realize the full SMDS synergies. Input cost (especially OCC, nat gas and freight) volatility could impact results as well.

Our price target is based on EV/EBITDA in line with EU Paper & Packaging sector peers' 5yr average multiple, reflecting Mondi's best- in- sector margins/ROCE and balance sheet. Key risks: 1) macro impacting demand; 2) industry supply; 3) packaging pricing; and 4) FX.
Our 2026E Price Target of \(55 is based on our\) 5,632 mil EBITDA estimate and an EV/EBITDA multiple of 7.1x.

Risks include the pace of synergy capture, fluctuations in containerboard and boxboard paper prices due to a supply / demand imbalance, new tariffs and other geopolitical complexities, FX, input cost volatility (notably OCC, transportation, and energy), and irrational behavior from non- integrated containerboard competitors.
